Description: Object carved from limestone, roughly rectangular in shape; top with projecting circle in raised relief and underside roughly flat; two opposite long sides incised with patterns, while the others are plain; one side has incised rectangles two of which contain different motifs and the other is deeply incised with what could look like a cursive script, though unidentified (previously mistakenly thought to be demotic); maybe a game piece (?); chipped in various places.
Curator's comments: There are two stone objects under these Register and Big Numbers. The original entry in the paper Register vol. 3 read:"2 Fragments of stone with marks in demotic etc.", but the "2" and the plural "s" have been crossed out. Two items retain the numbers, however.
The register states 'Hellenion' as the findspot, by which the Great Temenos is meant, which Petrie (erroneously) identified as the 'Hellenion'.
Bibliographic references: Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (TH.45)
